  <detection>
    - Use constant-time comparison functions
    - Implement rate limiting
    - Add random delays to responses
    - Monitor for systematic probing
    - Audit cryptographic implementations
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Detect timing variation in target
    - Successfully extract character-by-character
    - Enumerate valid usernames
    - Quantify timing differential
    - Document statistical significance
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Take many samples - 1000+ measurements reduce noise
    - Test from same network segment if possible
    - Early morning = less server load = cleaner signals
    - Use TCP timestamps for microsecond precision
    - Python hmac.compare_digest() is constant-time
    - Java MessageDigest.isEqual() is constant-time
    - String == comparison is almost never constant-time
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Timing attacks exploit the difference between "quick failure" and "slow failure." Every early return, every short-circuit evaluation, every non-constant-time operation is a potential leak. The fix is simple in theory - make all operations take the same time regardless of input. In practice, finding and fixing all timing vulnerabilities is challenging.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
